<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[174,1233,1222,1857]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
Diagnosis. Both sexes of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1817" box="[571,732,1478,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferruginea">
<emphasis box="[571,732,1478,1504]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ferruginea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clearly differ from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stackelberg" authorityYear="1952" box="[981,1102,1479,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ingrica">
<emphasis box="[981,1102,1479,1504]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ingrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1123,1223,1478,1505]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[166,1225,261,1679]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Hammerschmidtia ferruginea (figs 1–4) from Rivne Region (Ukraine) and H. ingrica (figs 5–8) from Moscow Region (Russia): 1, 5 — habitus, male, dorsal view; 2, 6 — habitus, female, dorsal view; 3, 7 — arista, male, lateral view; 4, 8 — thorax, female, ventral view (arrow shows the pilosity of the posterior part of the katepisternum and hind coxa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">figs 5–8</figureCitation>
) by the longer body, 9.0– 
<quantity box="[475,559,1510,1537]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="13.0">13 mm</quantity>
(in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stackelberg" authorityYear="1952" box="[615,734,1511,1536]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ingrica">
<emphasis box="[615,734,1511,1536]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ingrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, body length 5.5–8.0 mm), and plumose arista (
<figureCitation box="[256,318,1542,1569]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[166,1225,261,1679]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Hammerschmidtia ferruginea (figs 1–4) from Rivne Region (Ukraine) and H. ingrica (figs 5–8) from Moscow Region (Russia): 1, 5 — habitus, male, dorsal view; 2, 6 — habitus, female, dorsal view; 3, 7 — arista, male, lateral view; 4, 8 — thorax, female, ventral view (arrow shows the pilosity of the posterior part of the katepisternum and hind coxa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">fig. 3</figureCitation>
), with its branches&gt; 2× as long as the maximum diameter of the arista (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stackelberg" authorityYear="1952" box="[174,288,1575,1600]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ingrica">
<emphasis box="[174,288,1575,1600]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ingrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, arista with shorter microtrichia (
<figureCitation box="[681,741,1574,1601]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[166,1225,261,1679]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Hammerschmidtia ferruginea (figs 1–4) from Rivne Region (Ukraine) and H. ingrica (figs 5–8) from Moscow Region (Russia): 1, 5 — habitus, male, dorsal view; 2, 6 — habitus, female, dorsal view; 3, 7 — arista, male, lateral view; 4, 8 — thorax, female, ventral view (arrow shows the pilosity of the posterior part of the katepisternum and hind coxa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">fig. 7</figureCitation>
), the longest branches slightly longer than the maximum diameter of the arista). Additionally, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1817" box="[799,956,1606,1632]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferruginea">
<emphasis box="[799,956,1606,1632]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ferruginea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be separated from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stackelberg" authorityYear="1952" box="[174,293,1639,1664]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ingrica">
<emphasis box="[174,293,1639,1664]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ingrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by: hind coxae covered with numerous short black setae (
<bibRefCitation author="Mutin, V. A. &amp; Barkalov, A. V." pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="342 - 500" refId="ref6373" refString="Mutin, V. A. &amp; Barkalov, A. V. 1999. Fam. Syrphidae - hoverflies. In: Lehr, P. A., ed. Key to the insects of Russian Far East. Vol. 6 (Diptera and Siphonaptera), pt. 1. Dalnauka Publishing House, Vladivostok, 342 - 500 [In Russian]." type="book chapter" year="1999">Mutin &amp; Barkalov, 1999</bibRefCitation>
) as well as katepisternum with several (8–12) long black setae posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[1120,1182,1670,1697]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[166,1225,261,1679]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Hammerschmidtia ferruginea (figs 1–4) from Rivne Region (Ukraine) and H. ingrica (figs 5–8) from Moscow Region (Russia): 1, 5 — habitus, male, dorsal view; 2, 6 — habitus, female, dorsal view; 3, 7 — arista, male, lateral view; 4, 8 — thorax, female, ventral view (arrow shows the pilosity of the posterior part of the katepisternum and hind coxa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">fig. 4</figureCitation>
) (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stackelberg" authorityYear="1952" box="[174,290,1703,1728]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ingrica">
<emphasis box="[174,290,1703,1728]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ingrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, katepisternum without black setae, and hind coxae mostly with 2–3 long black setae only in outer posterior corner laterally and the same amount at the posterior edge, as on 
<figureCitation box="[213,271,1766,1793]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[166,1225,261,1679]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Hammerschmidtia ferruginea (figs 1–4) from Rivne Region (Ukraine) and H. ingrica (figs 5–8) from Moscow Region (Russia): 1, 5 — habitus, male, dorsal view; 2, 6 — habitus, female, dorsal view; 3, 7 — arista, male, lateral view; 4, 8 — thorax, female, ventral view (arrow shows the pilosity of the posterior part of the katepisternum and hind coxa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">fig. 8</figureCitation>
); female tergite 2 (
<figureCitation box="[493,554,1766,1793]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[166,1225,261,1679]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Hammerschmidtia ferruginea (figs 1–4) from Rivne Region (Ukraine) and H. ingrica (figs 5–8) from Moscow Region (Russia): 1, 5 — habitus, male, dorsal view; 2, 6 — habitus, female, dorsal view; 3, 7 — arista, male, lateral view; 4, 8 — thorax, female, ventral view (arrow shows the pilosity of the posterior part of the katepisternum and hind coxa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">fig. 2</figureCitation>
) usually with pale anterolateral part that do not look like separate maculae (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stackelberg" authorityYear="1952" box="[425,541,1799,1824]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hammerschmidtia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ingrica">
<emphasis box="[425,541,1799,1824]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">H. ingrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, female tergites 2 and often 3 with pale maculae that look like a separate maculae (
<figureCitation box="[458,519,1830,1857]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1723,1745]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,261,1679]" captionTargetId="figure-14@2.[166,1225,261,1679]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Hammerschmidtia ferruginea (figs 1–4) from Rivne Region (Ukraine) and H. ingrica (figs 5–8) from Moscow Region (Russia): 1, 5 — habitus, male, dorsal view; 2, 6 — habitus, female, dorsal view; 3, 7 — arista, male, lateral view; 4, 8 — thorax, female, ventral view (arrow shows the pilosity of the posterior part of the katepisternum and hind coxa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6377544" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6377544/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">fig. 6</figureCitation>
), especially on tergite 2).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
